## Conceptual Summary
Awareness Theory explains cognition as a **visibility‑driven, resolution‑weighted, gradient‑structured system**.  
It integrates:
- awareness (visibility)  
- awareness gradients (direction)  
- awareness resolution (clarity)  
- awareness failure modes (breakdown)  
- awareness repair (restoration)  

Together, these documents form a complete model of how awareness emerges, stabilizes, destabilizes, and recovers.

---

## Relationship to Other HERMES Modules
Awareness Theory connects directly to:
- **Identity Theory** (visibility of identity structure)  
- **Contradiction Theory** (visibility of contradictions)  
- **Field Dynamics** (gradient illumination)  
- **Recursion Theory** (recursive magnification of awareness)  
- **HERMES Runtime** (operators for awareness manipulation: ILLUMINATE, RESOLVE, STABILIZE)  

Awareness is one of the core perceptual layers of the unified cognitive architecture.

